{"type":"text","timestamp":1777217556854,"sessionID":"ses_235946bdeffeassGe35zNICnSq","part":{"id":"prt_dca6bbf00001EES2PNoeKzLNpc","messageID":"msg_dca6b96110012PwjwdQo4PZGc1","sessionID":"ses_235946bdeffeassGe35zNICnSq","type":"text","text":"The **echo-cascade verifier** is a fictional CRDT replication primitive that detects lost updates through cascaded echoes. When a replica applies a write, it emits an \"echo\" — a lightweight causal message — that propagates through the replica topology along causal paths. Each hop increments a hop counter, and the cascade depth is fixed at **7**. If an echo returns to the originating replica having traversed the full cascade without encountering a conflicting write, the update is considered durable. If an echo is lost, diverges, or encounters a newer version before completing the cascade, the originating replica flags a potential lost update and triggers reconciliation. The fixed depth of 7 bounds worst-case detection latency while ensuring coverage across typical multi-datacenter topologies.","time":{"start":1777217556852,"end":1777217556852}}}
